The Administrator's Favor

The Kesharat overseer stands beneath the half-built signal tower, her ledger open against her hip. Three clan workers sit in the tower's shadow with their hands bound behind them. The overseer sees your ring before she sees your face. "Perfect timing," she says. "You understand contracts. These three signed on for tower construction at standard wage. Now they claim the site is sacred ground and they won't work."

She gestures to a pile of tools untouched since morning. "I have quotas. The rail schedule doesn't care about local superstitions." Her voice drops, confiding. "But if a Guild representative witnessed them breaking contract, my report becomes documentation. The Administration respects mercantile law. We could resolve this cleanly."

One of the bound workers meets your eyes. His lips are cracked from thirst despite the water barrel twenty paces away. The overseer's assistant stands beside it, hand resting on a truncheon. She hasn't offered them a drink all afternoon.

The overseer turns a page in her ledger, pen ready. "I just need your mark and a brief statement. Then I can process their breach and hire replacements. The clans respect the Guild, and your word carries weight they'll accept." She holds out the pen. The ink is already drying in the heat.

